# Rust Async & Concurrency

Rust async is zero-cost but not zero-complexity. Choose the right model before writing a single `async fn`.

## When to use async

| Workload | Model |
|---|---|
| I/O-bound (network, disk, DB) | `async`/`await` with tokio |
| CPU-bound computation | `rayon` thread pool or `std::thread::spawn` |
| CPU-bound inside async | `tokio::task::spawn_blocking` |
| Shared state across threads | `Arc<Mutex<T>>` or `Arc<RwLock<T>>` |
| Message passing | `tokio::sync::mpsc` / `tokio::sync::oneshot` |

## Rules

- Never call blocking I/O or `std::thread::sleep` inside an `async fn` â€” it starves the executor
- Use `tokio::time::sleep` / `tokio::time::timeout` for all async timing
- Wrap every long CPU operation with `tokio::task::spawn_blocking` so it runs on the blocking thread pool
- Prefer structured concurrency with `tokio::task::JoinSet` or `futures::future::join_all` over unbounded spawning
- Always `await` or explicitly drop `JoinHandle`s â€” orphaned tasks hide errors and leak resources
- Apply `tokio::time::timeout` to every external call; never await without a deadline

## Cancellation safety

- Know which futures are cancellation-safe: `tokio::sync::Mutex::lock` is; most I/O futures are not when partially complete
- Use `tokio::select!` carefully â€” a branch that is cancelled mid-way may leave state inconsistent
- Document `// cancellation safe` or `// NOT cancellation safe` on any `async fn` that is `select!`-ed

## Channels

- Use `mpsc` for fan-in (many producers, one consumer)
- Use `broadcast` for fan-out (one producer, many consumers)
- Use `oneshot` for a single response to a request
- Always handle the `Err` from channel sends â€” a dropped receiver is a logic error, not noise

## Trait objects and async

- `async fn` in traits requires the `async-trait` crate OR Rust 1.75+ return-position `impl Trait` in traits
- Prefer static dispatch (`impl Future`) over `Box<dyn Future>` in hot paths

## Testing async code

```rust
#[tokio::test]
async fn test_fetch() {
    let result = fetch("http://example.com").await.unwrap();
    assert!(!result.is_empty());
}

// For timeouts in tests:
#[tokio::test(flavor = "multi_thread")]
async fn test_with_timeout() {
    let result = tokio::time::timeout(
        Duration::from_secs(5),
        fetch("http://example.com"),
    )
    .await
    .expect("timed out")
    .expect("fetch failed");
}
```

- Use `#[tokio::test]` for unit tests; use `tokio::test(flavor = "multi_thread")` only when you need real parallelism
- Never spawn a real `tokio::Runtime` inside a `#[tokio::test]` â€” use `tokio::runtime::Handle::current()` instead
